(601, 25, 'What does the CIA triad stand for in information security?', 'Central Intelligence Agency', 'Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability', 'Control, Identification, Authentication', 'Cryptography, Intrusion, Attack', 2, 1),
(602, 25, 'What is phishing?', 'An automated tool that scans networks for open ports', 'A social engineering attack where attackers send deceptive messages to trick users into revealing sensitive data', 'A mechanism to filter spam emails', 'A type of physical security device that blocks unauthorized access to server rooms', 2, 1),
(603, 25, 'What does the term ''malware'' stand for?', 'Malicious Software', 'Malfunctioning Hardware', 'Multi-layered Warehouse', 'Mailbox Warehousing', 1, 1),
(604, 25, 'What is a firewall in computer networks?', 'A physical wall built to protect servers from catching fire', 'A security system that monitors and filters incoming and outgoing network traffic based on predetermined rules', 'A software tool that increases internet download speeds', 'A type of secure password manager', 2, 1),
(605, 25, 'What is the main security advantage of Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)?', 'It remembers passwords for you automatically', 'It adds extra security layers, requiring multiple independent credentials to verify identity', 'It increases network bandwidth', 'It encrypts stored local files', 2, 1),
(606, 25, 'What is ransomware?', 'Software that generates random numbers for passwords', 'Malicious software that encrypts a victim''s files and demands payment in exchange for the decryption key', 'A tool to track user keystrokes in real time', 'A protocol that speeds up secure cloud backups', 2, 1),
(607, 25, 'What does HTTPS stand for, and what makes it different from HTTP?', 'Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure; it encrypts the communication channel between the client and server', 'Hypertext Transfer Protocol Static; it is only used for static web pages', 'Hypertext Transfer Protocol Speed; it is a faster version of HTTP', 'Hypertext Transfer Protocol Shared; it allows multiple users to share a connection', 1, 1),
(608, 25, 'What is a DDoS attack?', 'Data Deletion and Overwriting System', 'Distributed Denial of Service; an attempt to make an online service unavailable by overwhelming it with traffic from multiple sources', 'Direct Database Overload System', 'Distributed Decryption of Secure Sockets', 2, 1),
(609, 25, 'What is SQL Injection (SQLi)?', 'An attack where malicious SQL statements are injected into input fields to manipulate backend databases', 'A method to accelerate database query speeds', 'A tool to import bulk data into a database table', 'An encryption algorithm for relational databases', 1, 1),
(610, 25, 'What is the primary purpose of using a Virtual Private Network (VPN)?', 'To increase physical hard drive storage', 'To encrypt internet traffic and mask your online identity/location by routing through a secure server', 'To scan local computer files for viruses', 'To host virtual reality applications online', 2, 1),
(611, 25, 'What is a ''zero-day'' vulnerability in cybersecurity?', 'A bug that is fixed within zero days of discovery', 'A software vulnerability that is unknown to the vendor, leaving no time to develop a patch before exploitation', 'A virus that deletes all files on day zero', 'A security system that requires zero configuration', 2, 1),
(612, 25, 'What is a brute force attack?', 'An automated trial-and-error method to guess passwords or cryptographic keys by trying all possible combinations', 'An automated trial-and-error method to guess passwords or cryptographic keys by trying all possible combinations', 'An injection of malicious script code into a web browser', 'A DDoS attack launched from smart mobile devices', 2, 1),
(613, 25, 'What is cryptography?', 'The study of underground cave formations', 'The practice and study of techniques for securing communication in the presence of adversaries through encryption', 'The process of writing bug-free software source code', 'A method to test the physical durability of hard drives', 2, 1),
(614, 25, 'What is the difference between symmetric and asymmetric encryption?', 'Symmetric uses the same key for both encryption and decryption; asymmetric uses a public/private key pair', 'Symmetric uses the same key for both encryption and decryption; asymmetric uses a public/private key pair', 'Symmetric is much slower and more secure than asymmetric', 'Symmetric is only used by web browsers, asymmetric by databases', 2, 1),
(615, 25, 'What is a Trojan Horse in computer security?', 'A security tool that blocks incoming malware', 'Malicious software disguised as legitimate, harmless, or useful software to trick users into executing it', 'A hardware firewall that shaped like a horse', 'A fast transmission line between two databases', 2, 1),
(616, 25, 'What is social engineering?', 'Designing software platforms for social networking sites', 'The psychological manipulation of people into performing actions or divesting confidential information', 'A method to build secure server rooms', 'A technique to organize team structures in IT projects', 2, 1),
(617, 25, 'What is a keylogger?', 'A hardware device that safely stores digital encryption keys', 'A type of surveillance software or hardware that records every keystroke made on a keyboard', 'A tool that unlocks computer screens automatically', 'A password generator based on keyword phrases', 2, 1),
(618, 25, 'What does SSL/TLS primarily protect?', 'It protects physical servers from getting overheated', 'It encrypts data transmitted between a web browser and a web server, preventing interception', 'It scans downloaded files for malicious code', 'It backups database contents to remote servers', 2, 1),
(619, 25, 'What is a security patch?', 'A physical sticker placed over a webcam for privacy', 'An update to a software program to fix a security vulnerability or bug', 'A piece of code that increases software processing speeds', 'A license key required to activate anti-virus tools', 2, 1),
(620, 25, 'What is Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)?', 'An attack where a user is tricked into clicking a malicious link outside the website', 'An injection vulnerability where malicious scripts are injected into trusted websites and executed in a victim''s browser', 'A way to share stylesheets across multiple websites', 'A script that converts HTML documents into PDF files', 2, 1),
(621, 25, 'What is the primary goal of Penetration Testing?', 'To install security software on client machines', 'To systematically and safely probe systems to identify and exploit vulnerabilities, assessing real-world security posture', 'To test the maximum internet download speed of a server', 'To train developers on how to type code faster', 2, 1),
(622, 25, 'What is a ''data breach''?', 'A physical breakage of a hard disk drive', 'An incident where confidential, protected, or sensitive data is viewed, copied, or stolen by an unauthorized individual', 'An intentional backup of data to multiple cloud accounts', 'A database system upgrade that modifies column names', 2, 1),
(623, 25, 'What is network sniffing?', 'Physically checking server cables for damage', 'The process of intercepting and logging network traffic (packets) passing through a network', 'Blocking unauthorized IP addresses from connecting to a router', 'Cleaning a system''s registry files', 2, 1),
(624, 25, 'What is an IP address?', 'An Intellectual Property rights identifier', 'A unique numerical label assigned to each device connected to a computer network that uses the Internet Protocol', 'The physical address of a company''s main server room', 'A secret password used to access network configurations', 2, 1),
(625, 25, 'What is biometric authentication?', 'A security check that tests the battery life of a device', 'An authentication method that uses unique biological characteristics, such as fingerprints or facial patterns, to verify identity', 'A program that measures the biological health of server room staff', 'An encryption algorithm based on DNA sequencing models', 2, 1),

